Preheat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Cut the @red onion{1} in half through the root,
peel and slice into thin half moon shapes. Cut each @chestnut mushrooms{1} into
four slices. Cut the @cherry tomatoes{1} in half. Pop your mushrooms and plum
tomatoes on a large lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle over some @oil{}, a pinch of
@salt{pinch} and a good grind of @black pepper{grind}. Give the tray a shake and
leave to the side for a few minutes.

To make the batter, put the @gram flour{175%g} in a large #bowl{} with a good
pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @black pepper{grind}. Whisk in the
@water{350%ml} with a #whisk{} or a #fork{}, until you are left with a smooth
batter (no lumps!). Pour your batter into a #measuring jug{}. Leave to the side
to stand for a few minutes (this is essential for pancake making).

Drizzle a good glug of @olive oil{glug} into a #saucepan{} on medium heat and
add your onion. Cook for ~{7%minutes}. Meanwhile, pop your mushrooms and
tomatoes on the top shelf of your oven for ~{15%minutes}.

When your onion has cooked for ~{7%minutes}, add the @balsamic vinegar{1}, pop a
lid on, turn the heat down to low and leave to cook for ~{8-10%minutes} until
nicely caramelised, then remove the pan from the heat and leave to the side.
Meanwhile, cut the @goat's cheese{1} into roughly 1cm chunks and leave to the side.

Pancake time! For the perfect pancake you need a hot pan. Drizzle some oil into
a medium-sized #frying pan{} (about 20cm wide), and put on high heat. Use
#kitchen paper{} to rub the excess oil away (careful not to burn yourself).

Once the pan is hot, pour in 75ml of batter (you will be making two pancakes per
person, but we've given you a bit of extra batter to practise with!). Quickly
tilt your pan to roll your batter around, until it covers the base of the
frying pan. Leave to cook for ~{2-3%minutes}, until you can see bubbles appearing
and your pancake comes away easily from the pan. Carefully flip and cook the
other side for ~{1-2%minutes}. Both sides should be golden - don't worry if your
first pancake isn't the prettiest, it's not a beauty pageant!

> Tip: If you only have a small frying pan, just use 50ml of batter per pancake
> and make more pancakes!

Once your veggies are roasted, remove them from your oven, drain off any excess
water and add to a bowl with your goat's cheese. Stir together to melt your cheese.

Plating up time! Take everything to the table - this is a fun one to serve
yourselves! We recommend adding a spoonful of your cheesy veggies to a pancake,
followed by a little caramelised red onion and a handful of @wild rocket{1},
then devouring your open pancakes.